  flashcards: [
    { front: "What is an element?", back: "A pure substance made of only one kind of atom; it cannot be broken down chemically into anything simpler." },
    { front: "How is the periodic table ordered?", back: "By increasing atomic (proton) number, left to right and top to bottom." },
    { front: "Atomic number vs mass number", back: "Atomic number = number of protons. Mass number = protons + neutrons." },
    { front: "How do you find the number of neutrons?", back: "Neutrons = mass number − atomic number." },
    { front: "Maximum electrons in the first three shells", back: "Shell 1: 2, shell 2: 8, shell 3: 8 (the 2, 8, 8 rule)." },
    { front: "What is a group?", back: "A vertical column. Members share the same number of outer electrons and have similar properties." },
    { front: "What is a period?", back: "A horizontal row. The period number equals the number of electron shells the atoms use." },
    { front: "Where are metals and non-metals?", back: "Metals on the left/centre, non-metals on the right, divided by the zig-zag staircase line." },
    { front: "Name three Group 1 alkali metals and the reactivity trend", back: "Lithium, sodium, potassium; reactivity INCREASES down the group." },
    { front: "What happens when an alkali metal meets water?", back: "It fizzes and reacts, releasing hydrogen gas and forming an alkaline solution." },
    { front: "Name the Group 7 halogens and the reactivity trend", back: "Fluorine, chlorine, bromine, iodine; reactivity DECREASES down the group." },
    { front: "Why are noble gases unreactive?", back: "They have a full outer shell of electrons, which is a very stable arrangement." },
    { front: "Why did Mendeleev leave gaps in his table?", back: "He left spaces for undiscovered elements and predicted their properties — later confirmed (e.g. germanium)." },
    { front: "What is a displacement reaction in Group 7?", back: "A more reactive halogen pushes a less reactive one out of its compound, e.g. chlorine displaces bromine." },
  ],

